A little ice cream turns Strawberry Pretzel cookies into a new summer treat! 🍓 🥨  Blend with ice cream then freeze into molds with strawberry sauce for Strawberry Pretzel Popsicles 🍦 

Cookies:
Ingredients:
	•	2 sticks + 2 tablespoons salted butter, melted and cooled
	•	1 cup brown sugar
	•	1 cup granulated sugar
	•	3 tsp vanilla extract
	•	2 large eggs
	•	2 and 1/2 cups flour
	•	1 tsp baking soda
	•	2 pinches of salt
	•	1 oz freeze-dried strawberries
	•	1 cup strawberry jam
	•	1 bag pretzel sticks

Instructions:
 Preheat oven to 375°F and line a baking sheet with parchment paper.
 In a stand mixer, cream together the melted butter, brown sugar, and granulated sugar. Whip the mixture until it becomes slightly lighter in color. 
		Beat in the vanilla. followed by the eggs, one at a time, mixing well after each addition.
 In a separate bowl, whisk together the flour, baking soda, and pinches of salt.
 Add the dry ingredient mixture to the wet ingredients, incorporating about 1/2 cup at a time. Stir until just combined.
 Gently fold in the freeze-dried strawberries.
 Spread the dough out onto a cookie sheet and refrigerate for 20 minutes to firm up.
 Dollop small spoonfuls of strawberry jam onto the dough. Then, gently fold the edges of the dough over and into the center to encapsulate the jam. Add a few more dollops of jam on top of the dough. 
		Return the cookie sheet to the refrigerator for an additional 20 minutes to chill.
 Using a 2-inch cookie scoop or a tablespoon, scoop the dough and roll each portion in crushed pretzels. 
		Place the coated cookie scoops on the prepared baking sheet, spacing them a couple inches apart.
 Freeze the cookie sheet with the dough for about 10-15 minutes to firm them up before baking.
 Bake the cookies in the preheated oven for approximately 13 minutes or until golden brown around the edges. Note that the baking time may be slightly longer since the cookies are baked from frozen.
 Remove the cookies from the oven and let them cool on the baking sheet for a 10 minutes, then transfer them to a wire rack to cool completely.
 Once cooled, enjoy these delicious Strawberry Pretzel Cookies, or transform them into a new treat!

The perfect afternoon coffee paring ☕️ 💗

Recipe below ⬇️ 

Ingredients: 
4 bananas
2 eggs
2 tsp Vanilla extract
1/4 cup canola oil
1/8th tsp almond extract
3/4 cup of brown sugar
2 1/2 cups flour
2 tsp baking powder
12 oz raspberries frozen or fresh
3/4 cup chocolate chips
Coarse sugar

Instructions:
Mash the banana in a large mixing bowl. Combine with the eggs, vanilla extract, canola oil, almond extract, and brown sugar. Stir the flour and baking powder into the wet ingredients until just combined. Gently mix in the raspberries and chocolate chips. 

Line a muffin pan with paper liners. Fill each liner with about 1/3 cup batter. Sprinkle the tops with coarse sugar. Bake at 425ºF for 7 minutes, then turn the temperature down to 350ºF and bake for 18-20 minutes more, or until a toothpick inserted in the center comes out clean. Allow the muffins to cool in the pan for 10 minutes before removing.

The harvest season is in full swing and it’s time to enjoy beautiful garden tomatoes! No matter what type of tomatoes you grow or find at a local farmer’s market, there is no shortage of ways to enjoy them. One of my favorite ways is simply sliced, over good grilled bread. Some people use a base of mayo, some use butter, and others still nothing but bread, tomatoes, and salt. I say all are good! But one of the most delicious ways to enjoy those juicy summer tomatoes is these Brown Butter Tomato Toasts. Warm, caramelized, toasted butter is drizzled over freshly sliced summer tomatoes. This adds a layer of richness and dimension to the toast that can’t be matched, plus it can be made in just minutes. Laid atop grilled bread and finished with coarse sea salt and pepper – those baskets of tomatoes will be gone before you know it.

Recipe below:

INGREDIENTS
 
3 tbsp salted butter
4 slices hearty bread
1 tbsp olive oil
2 large tomatoes preferably heirloom
coarse sea salt
freshly cracked black pepper

INSTRUCTIONS
 
Brown the butter: In a small saute pan over medium heat, melt the butter. Continue stirring and cooking the butter after it has fully melted; it should start to bubble.
As the butter cooks, the color will slowly change to a golden brown and it will smell nutty and caramelized. Pull the butter off the heat once a light brown color has been reached, about 3-4 minutes total.
Brush both sides of each piece of bread with a little olive oil. Grill over high heat until toasted, 1-2 minutes per side.
Thickly slice the tomatoes. Layer tomato slices over the grilled bread.
Drizzle the browned butter over the tomatoes, then sprinkle with salt and pepper.
Serve immediately.

These Japanese Deviled Eggs are the perfect unexpected twist on the classic appetizer. Umami-rich miso sauce from @saucebycheftai adds a rich base of flavor while crunchy sesame seeds and spicy Mayo bring in classic notes from Japanese cuisine. Honestly? These deviled eggs taste *almost* like sushi 🍣. Try them for yourself with the recipe below ⬇️ 

Ingredients:

-6 large eggs
-3 tbsp mayonnaise 
-2 tbsp miso sauce (I used @saucebycheftai miso sauce)
-1 tbsp soy sauce 
-black pepper, to taste
-sesame seeds
-scallions, sliced 
-spicy Mayo 

Instructions:
	•	Bring a pot of water to a boil. Use a spoon to lower the eggs into the water. Set a timer for 13 minutes. 
	•	While the eggs are boiling prepare an ice water bath. After 13 minutes, place the eggs in the ice water.
	•	Once the eggs have cooled, peel them and slice in half lengthwise. Remove the yolk to a small bowl with a spoon and set the whites aside.
	•	Mash the yolks with a fork and add the mayonnaise, miso sauce, soy sauce, and black pepper. Thoroughly mix into a smooth filling. 
 • Sprinkle a layer of sesame seeds onto a plate, then press the cut sides of each egg white into the seeds.
	•	Use a spoon to add a portion of the deviled egg mixture back into the each egg white (or use a piping bag).
 •Garnish the eggs with a drizzle of spicy Mayo and a sprinkle of scallions

It’s finally FALL! 🍁 Today is the true first day of autumn so we are celebrating with these Pumpkin Cupcakes with Brown Butter-Sage Frosting. Moist, spiced pumpkin cake topped with fluffy, rich, brown butter frosting makes all my autumn dreams come true. These are the perfect cozy, comforting, festive cupcakes to kick off the season. Recipe below 🍂

Cupcakes:
1 cup all purpose flour
1 teaspoon baking powder
½ teaspoon baking soda
1 1/2 tsp pumpkin pie spice
1 tsp cinnamon
¼ teaspoon salt
2 large eggs
1 15oz can pumpkin puree
½ cup granulated sugar
½ cup brown sugar, lightly packed
1/4 cup vegetable oil
1/4 cup melted butter
2 tsp pure vanilla extract

Fill a muffin tin with 12 liners. 
Whisk together the flour, baking powder, baking soda, pumpkin pie spice, cinnamon, and salt. 
In a large bowl, whisk together the eggs, canned pumpkin, brown and granulated sugar, oil, melted butter, and vanilla. Add the flour mixture to the wet ingredients and whisk until almost fully smooth. 
Divide the batter evenly between the cupcake liners and bake for 25-30 minutes at 350°F, or until a knife comes out clean. Cool the cupcakes in the pan for 5 minutes, then removed the cupcakes to a rack to cool completely before frosting.

Sage-Brown Butter Frosting:
1 1/2 sticks butter, browned and cooled to room temp
1 stick softened butter
1 tsp vanilla bean paste 
4 cups powdered sugar, sifted 
1 tsp salt
1 tbsp heavy cream
2 tbsp fresh sage leaves 

With a hand mixer or stand mixer, whip together the cooled brown butter and softened butter for 3-4 minutes until fluffy. Whip in the vanilla bean paste. Whip the powdered sugar into the butter, a heaping spoonful at a time, on low speed. Continue until all sugar has been incorporated. Whip in the salt for 1 minute, then add the heavy cream. Whip for 5 more minutes on medium speed until fluffy. 

If using the sage, fry the sage in a tablespoon of butter until crisp. Crumble atop the frosted cupcakes.

Spooky Broken Glass Red Velvet Cupcakes 👻 🩸 My sister and I are absolutely obsessed with Halloween. From the spooky music, haunted houses, and dressing in costumes to carving pumpkins and everything in between - we love this time of year. So naturally, festive food is high on our list. My sister has been making these creepy yet delectable Spooky Broken Glass Red Velvet Cupcakes for a few years now, and they just keep getting better. Tender, fluffy red velvet cake studded with mini chocolate chips is covered in sweet and tangy cream cheese frosting. Shards of candy glass pierce through the frosting for an eerie touch.
Shockingly realistic fake blood is the final touch on these gory, terrifyingly delicious treats. These cupcakes will be the star of any Halloween party and make for the perfect final bite on a cold Halloween night.

Find the recipe at the link in my bio or at https:// www.fortheperfectbite.com/spooky-broken-glass-red-velvet-cupcakes/

Everybody loves fondue. What’s not to like? Melty, smooth, creamy cheese, a variety of dipping options, and a fun, shared eating experience. What you may not know, however, is how easy it is to make fondue at home. If you have a few cheeses, a little wine, and a splash of bourbon, you have everything you need for a fast, delicious, and downright festive fondue. This fondue uses smoked Gouda for a touch of smoke flavor, perfect for fall. A finish of bourbon adds a hint of vanilla and oak to the creamy cheese. I like to serve this with cubes of french bread, honey wheat bread, apples, and carrots. But there’s almost nothing you can dip in this fondue that won’t taste good.

Recipe at the link in my bio and at https://www.fortheperfectbite.com/smoked-bourbon-fondue/

The air has begun to cool and fall has set in. With days getting shorter and nights getting colder, we could all use a cozy dinner for comfort and warmth. This Creamy Caramelized Onion, Mushroom, and White Wine Chicken is perfect for the occasion. Chicken is seared to a perfect golden brown before the same pan is used to soften and caramelize onions and mushrooms. White wine is used to soak up all the flavors of the pan and form the base for a flavorful cream sauce. Spooned over pasta, this recipe is the epitome of comfort. I used fusilli col buco as my pasta of choice for the beautiful spirals and fun texture, but any long pasta would work here. This is the perfect dish to warm your kitchen, your body, and your soul on a chilly autumn night. 

Recipe at the link in my bio and at https://www.fortheperfectbite.com/creamy-caramelized-onion-mushroom-and-white-wine-chicken/

Classic Pumpkin Pie is one of my favorite desserts of all time. In fact, I have pumpkin pie instead of cake almost every year on my birthday. There’s just something so comforting about the creamy pumpkin filling, flavored with plenty of fall spices and baked in a flaky and buttery crust. No holiday gathering would be complete without it. The good news is, it’s easy to make! Out of all pies, pumpkin is one of the simplest and least fussy. The filling and the crust cook at the same time, no pre-cooking or blind baking necessary. But the reward is well worth it. The scent alone as it bakes will fill your kitchen with classic holiday joy. Top with a swirl of whipped cream and enjoy the most iconic holiday treat I can think of.

Recipe at link in my bio and at https://www.fortheperfectbite.com/classic-pumpkin-pie/

This Mushroom Arancini with Gruyere is the perfect way to use up leftover risotto, or the perfect excuse to whip up a fresh batch. The combination of flavors and textures in these arancini make them truly delectable. A crispy, golden brown exterior. Tender, earthy risotto inside. A core of melty, sharp Gruyere. Homemade Christmas Tree Snack Cakes! 🎄 these cute cakes are a fun and delicious treat to make at home and they taste even better than the nostalgic snack from the store!

Recipe ❄️ 
For the cake:

	•	1 1/2 cups all-purpose flour 
	•	1 tsp baking powder
	•	1/4 tsp salt
	•	4 eggs, separated into whites and yolks, at room temperature
	•	1 cup granulated sugar, divided
	•	4 tbsp vegetable oil
	•	4 tbsp water
	•	2 tsp vanilla extract
	•	1/8 tsp cream of tartar 

For the frosting:

	•	1 cup salted butter, softened
	•	1 1/2 cups powdered sugar
	•	2 tsp vanilla extract
	•	1 tsp almond extract (optional)
	•	7 oz marshmallow fluff

For decorating:

	•	20 oz. white chocolate wafers for coating
	•	Green sprinkles
	•	Red food dye

To make the cake: Whip the egg whites with the cream of tartar and half the sugar until stiff. Beat the egg yolks and the rest of the sugar together until thicker and paler, then add the oil, water, and vanilla. Whisk together the flour, salt, and baking powder in a separate bowl, then sift 1/3 of the flour mixture into the egg yolk mixture. Fold in 1/3 of the merengue. Continue adding the flour and merengue in stages until the batter is light and airy. Spread the batter over a baking sheet prepared with parchment paper and bake at 350°F for 15-20 minutes, until just set. 

To make the frosting: in a large bowl, whip the softened butter until fluffy, then mix in the powdered sugar, vanilla and almond extract, and marshmallow fluff and whip for 4 minutes. 

Using a Christmas tree shaped cookie cutter, cut out shapes from the cooled cake. Slice each tree in half horizontally, spread a layer of frosting onto the bottom layer, and top with the other half of the cake to form a sandwich. Melt the white chocolate wafers and dip each tree sandwich into the melted chocolate, ensuring even coating. Sprinkle with green sprinkles. Dye the remaining melted white chocolate red and pipe garland onto the trees. 

Allow to set and enjoy!

Still so obsessed with these festive ravioli! 🎁 🎄 These are filled with a delicious beet filling (recipe below) and topped with a nutmeg-orange butter sauce. Warming, hearty flavors all around!

Beet Filling:

There’s so much to love about the nostalgic feeling and hustle and bustle of the city during the holidays!

Merry Christmas Eve Eve! 🎅 We thought it was time to bring back a classic holiday dessert: the Yule Log! Just tried some of our favorite AYCE sushi, just 30 minutes outside Pittsburgh, in Greensburg, Pa! 🍣 Mr. Tokyo 🍣 For $24, you can pick from a variety of classic and speciality sushi rolls, as well as soup, salad, appetizers, hibachi entrees, and ice cream, and have as much as you’d like! 🍱 We *certainly* got our moneys worth today. The NFL playoffs are here and it’s time to plan your gameday menu! 🏈 If you’re in need of a quick, easy, fun, and incredibly delicious snack, appetizer, or meal – I’ve got you covered. These Smoked Turkey, Swiss, and Dijon Pull-Apart Sliders with Garlic Butter are a snap to throw together but pack big flavor and melted cheesy goodness. The creamy dijon spread is really the key ingredient here. The sauce soaks into the bread, tying the flavors together and adding its own punchy bite. Melty swiss cheese complements the smoky turkey and makes for an incredible cheese pull. And lastly, you can’t forget about that garlic butter. It’s the final touch that takes these sliders from yummy – to addicting. My advice? Double the recipe.

Crimini Mushroom Risotto 🍄 Winter is really settling in, and I’m definitely craving cozy comfort food. And as far as comfort food goes, risotto is near the top of my list. This Crimini Mushroom Risotto checks all of the boxes – creamy, warm, earthy, cheesy – its pretty perfect. Although there are many ways to make mushroom risotto, I wanted this one to be perfectly smooth, so I finely minced the mushrooms after roasting them. The result is a perfectly cozy bowl of tender rice with deep mushroom flavor.
